0.body: POEM In the world of beats and melodies, A singer sought new harmonies. Python's code, a language unknown, They embraced with a spirit of their own. From verses to loops, they took the stride, Syntax and rhythm began to collide. A producer's flair and coder's grace, In this fusion of talents, they found their place. Through errors and trials, they persevered, With each bug conquered, they cheered. A snake game was born, a masterpiece grand, Crafted by their skillful hand. By ChatGPT Welcome! Are you completely new to programming and does your name start with E? Then this tutorial is made for you - literally! The aim is to take you from a complete beginner to a Python pro, in a short amount of time. To prove your Python mastery at the end, you will be tasked with creating a Snake game from scratch. Sounds like fun! Good luck 😎
0.title: Introduction

1.body: On the left hand side, you will find a list of tutorial chapters. Each chapter introduces new concepts and provides suitable problems for practising. The problems are designed to be used in conjunction with real life tutoring - there is not enough information solely in this course to learn Python from scratch. Some of the problems have a provided solution which can be viewed. To maximize your learning, you should not view these solutions before trying your best to solve the problem at hand. Even if you cannot figure it out right away, think for a while or ask your tutor before you move on to viewing the actual solution.

11.body: Experiment with using startswith, endswith, lower and upper to improve the checking of strings. Make a program which determines if last name is Sandström or first name is William. The program shouldn't care about big or small letters. Using while loops, add numbers given from a user until they enter a negative number. At this point, you should print the sum.

11.title: Already completed

12.body: In this exercise, you will create a program which repeatedly asks a user for password. You will successively add more functionality to the program. Part 1: Make a program which asks a user for a secret password. If the password is correct, tell them a supersecret phrase of your choosing. Part 2: If the user types quit or exit, the program should exit without saying the supersecret phrase. Part 3: The user should only have 3 attempts to type in the password. If they exceed this amount of attempts, the program should exit. Part 1 Example Solution password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") while password != "supersecretpassword": print("Incorrect password! Try again") password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") print("You entered the correct password, good job! :D") Part 2 Example Solution password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") while password != "supersecretpassword" and password != "quit" and password != "exit": print("Incorrect password! Try again") password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") if password == "supersecretpassword": print("You entered the correct password, good job! :D") else: print("Bye bye, sucker") Part 3 Example Solution password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") tries_left = 2 while password != "supersecretpassword" and password != "quit" and password != "exit" and tries_left > 0: print("Incorrect password! Try again") password = input("Please enter the secret password: ") tries_left = tries_left - 1 if password == "supersecretpassword": print("You entered the correct password, good job! :D") elif tries_left = 0: print("Too many failed attempts!") else: print("Bye bye, sucker") Can you solve this differently using 'break'? Are there any benefits or drawbacks to doing it this way?

12.title: Enter the secret password

6.body: Learned concepts: Printing text to the terminal using print Storing values in variables, ex a = 3 Adding, subtracting, multiplying and diving numbers and variables. Ex. c = a + b or c = 3 + b Getting input from a user using input() Variable types. Variables can have different types, such as: int - Integers (heltal) string - Strings (text) float - decimal numbers bool - boolean value, can be True or False Types can be converted to other types, ex int("3") converts "3" to an integer.
6.title: Summary:

8.body: Learned concepts bool (boolean) types. Comparing numbers using comparisons to produce True or False values. These can be used in if-statements. a > b = a is greater than b a < b = a is less than b a >= b = a is greater than or equal to b a <= b = a is less than or equal to b a == b = a is equal to b a != b = a is not equal to b a or b = a or b a and b <=> a and b not a = not a If statements can be used to run some code based on a condition. By adding an elif statement afterwards, another if statement can be checked, if the first one is incorrect. An else statement will run if the previous if statement condition was false.
